= Introduction to Plant Embryogenesis

- Land plants comprise a monophyletic group called *embryophytes* (有胚植物) - plants that make embryos
- What distinguishes land plants from aquatic algae is the ability to develop a multicellular *sporophyte* (孢子体) following fertilization
- The *zygote* (受精卵) - fertilized egg cell - has different fates among plant groups

== Bryophytes vs. Vascular Plants

- In nonvascular land plants (*bryophytes*, 苔藓植物) such as mosses:
  - The zygote produces a diploid sporophyte dependent on the *gametophyte* (配子体)
  - Minimal cell differentiation occurs
  - Simple stalk and capsule form without true vascular tissue
- In *vascular plants* (*tracheophytes*, 维管植物):
  - The zygote produces a diploid sporophyte that lives independently
  - Cells differentiate into three main tissue types: *dermal* (表皮组织), *ground* (基本组织), and *vascular tissues* (维管组织)
  - These tissues become specialized into various cell types comprising major organ systems

== Seed Plant Embryogenesis

- In *seed plants* (*spermatophytes*, 种子植物) including gymnosperms and angiosperms:
  - Embryogenesis terminates with formation of a dormant or *quiescent seed* (休眠种子)
  - This contrasts with the haploid spore as resting stage in bryophytes and non-seed plants
  - Seed plant embryogenesis evolved about 320 million years ago
  - Derived from a much older process defining land plants since their origin about 450 million years ago

== Key Developmental Processes

- Embryogenesis transforms the single-celled zygote into a complex, multicellular individual within a mature seed
- Provides examples of developmental processes establishing basic plant architecture:
  - *Morphogenesis* (形态发生) - elaboration of forms
  - *Organogenesis* (器官发生) - formation of functionally organized structures
  - *Histogenesis* (组织发生) - differentiation of cells to produce anatomically and functionally distinct tissues
- Essential feature: presence of *apical meristems* (顶端分生组织) at shoot and root tips
- Apical meristems sustain *indeterminate growth patterns* (无限生长模式)
- Embryo development features complex physiological changes:
  - Enable embryo to withstand prolonged *dormancy* (休眠) with reduced metabolic activity
  - Recognize and respond to environmental cues signaling *germination* (萌发) and growth resumption

= Embryogenesis in Monocots and Eudicots

== Comparison of Maize and Arabidopsis

- Maize (corn; *Zea mays*, 玉米) represents *monocots* (单子叶植物)
- *Arabidopsis* (拟南芥) represents *eudicots* (真双子叶植物)
- These represent opposite ends of a spectrum:
  - Maize: relatively complex and less predictable development
  - Arabidopsis: relatively simple and more predictable development

== Common Features

- Despite differences, several common themes generalize to all seed plants
- Most fundamental relates to *polarity* (极性):
  - *Apical-basal axis* (顶-基轴) runs between tips of embryonic shoot and root
  - *Radial axis* (径向轴) perpendicular to apical-basal axis, extends from center outward

#figure(
  image(images.at("22.3").path, width: 50%),
)

- The seedling shows two perpendicular organizational axes:
  - Longitudinal cross section: apical-basal axis from shoot apex to root tip
  - Transverse cross section: radial axis from vascular center through ground tissue to epidermis
- These axes are established during embryogenesis and guide tissue organization

== Stages of Maize Embryogenesis

#figure(
  image(images.at("22.1").path, width: 50%),
)

- Maize embryogenesis progresses through distinct stages:
  - *Zygotic stage* (合子期): Initial single-cell stage after fertilization
  - *Globular stage* (球形胚期): Spherical embryo with basic differentiation
  - *Transition stage* (过渡期): Not always clearly defined
  - *Coleoptile stage* (胚芽鞘期): Formation of coleoptile, scutellum, shoot and root apical meristems, radicle, and coleorhiza
  - *Leaf primordia stage* (叶原基期): Emergence of first leaf structures
  - *Maturation stage* (成熟期): Fully developed embryo ready for dormancy
- Characterized by less predictable cell division patterns compared to Arabidopsis
- The *scutellum* (盾片) is the single cotyledon characteristic of monocots

== Stages of Arabidopsis Embryogenesis

#figure(
  image(images.at("22.2").path, width: 50%),
)

- Arabidopsis shows highly stereotyped, precise cell division patterns:
  - *One-cell embryo*: After first asymmetric zygotic division forming apical and basal cells
  - *Two-cell embryo*: With distinct cell fates already specified
  - *Eight-cell embryo*: Two tiers of four cells each
  - *Mid-globular stage*: Distinct *protoderm* (原表皮) surface layer
  - *Early heart stage* (早期心形胚): Emerging *cotyledon primordia* (子叶原基)
  - *Late heart stage* (晚期心形胚): Clear bilateral symmetry
  - *Torpedo stage* (鱼雷胚): Elongated *hypocotyl* (下胚轴)
  - *Mature embryo* (成熟胚): All major tissues differentiated
- Simple and predictable pattern makes Arabidopsis an excellent model for studying molecular mechanisms

= Establishment of Apical-Basal Polarity

== Pattern Formation During Embryogenesis

#figure(
  image(images.at("22.4").path, width: 50%),
)

- Pattern formation involves clonally related groups of cells contributing to specific seedling structures
- Following asymmetric zygotic division:
  - Smaller apical daughter cell divides to form eight-cell embryo with upper and lower tiers
  - *Upper tier* (上层): Generates shoot apical meristem and most cotyledon primordia
  - *Lower tier* (下层): Forms hypocotyl, portions of cotyledons, embryonic root, and upper root apical meristem cells
  - *Basal cell* (基细胞): Produces *suspensor* (胚柄) connecting embryo to maternal tissue
- Position-dependent mechanisms determine cell fate during development

== Cytoskeletal Dynamics and Polarity Establishment

#figure(
  image(images.at("22.5").path, width: 50%),
)

- Live-cell imaging reveals cytoskeletal reorganization during early development:
  - Following fertilization, zygote shrinks and cortical *microtubules* (微管) become randomly oriented
  - Zygote bulges apically where transverse microtubule rings form
  - This bulge develops into the apical cell; base becomes basal cell
  - Microtubule reorganization precedes and directs asymmetric cell division
- *Cytoskeleton* (细胞骨架) plays crucial role in establishing and maintaining polarity
- The first division of the zygote is asymmetric, producing cells with different sizes and fates

== Periclinal and Anticlinal Cell Divisions

#figure(
  image(images.at("22.6").path, width: 50%),
)

- Two types of cell division orientations are critical for tissue patterning:
  - *Periclinal divisions* (平周分裂): Cell walls parallel to tissue surface
    - Contribute to establishment of new tissue layers
    - Example: protoderm formation
  - *Anticlinal divisions* (垂周分裂): Cell walls perpendicular to tissue surface
    - Increase cell numbers within existing layers
    - Do not change layer number
- Balance of these division planes is critical for proper radial patterning
- At eight-cell stage, cells divide periclinally to form protoderm, which becomes *epidermis* (表皮)

== Regulation of Cell Division Orientation

#figure(
  image(images.at("22.7").path, width: 50%),
)

- Cell division orientation can follow different patterns:
  - *Symmetric anticlinal division*: Through cell center following minimum surface area rule
    - Generates two equal-volume daughter cells
  - *Asymmetric periclinal division*: Under regulatory control (e.g., auxin signaling)
    - Deviates from minimum surface area rule
    - Generates distinct outer and inner cell layers
- Chemical signals like *auxin* (生长素) can override geometric constraints
- This demonstrates how molecular regulation guides proper tissue patterning

= Mechanisms Guiding Embryogenesis

== Position-Dependent Cell Fate Determination

#figure(
  image(images.at("22.8").path, width: 50%),
)

- Cell fates are not rigidly determined by lineage but by position-dependent signals
- Clonal analysis using GUS reporter system tracks individual cell descendants
- Variable positions of marked cell descendants in different organs demonstrate:
  - Cell fate is determined by cellular position and signaling environment
  - Not by strict lineage inheritance
- Supports importance of *position-dependent mechanisms* (位置依赖机制) in plant development
- Cells respond to their local environment to adopt appropriate fates

== Robustness of Pattern Formation

#figure(
  image(images.at("22.9").path, width: 50%),
)

- Extra cell divisions do not block establishment of basic radial pattern elements
- *FASS* gene mutants cannot form *preprophase bands* (前期带) of microtubules
- fass mutants show:
  - Highly irregular cell division and expansion planes
  - Severe morphological deformation
  - Despite abnormalities, recognizable tissues and organs form in correct positions
  - Radially oriented tissue patterns persist
- Demonstrates that positional information, not precise cell division patterns, primarily governs tissue identity
- Pattern formation mechanisms are robust to perturbations in cell division

== Intercellular Communication During Development

#figure(
  image(images.at("22.10").path, width: 50%),
)

- The potential for intercellular protein movement changes during development
- *Plasmodesmata* (胞间连丝) allow cell-to-cell movement of molecules
- Protein movement depends on size and developmental stage:
  - Small proteins move readily at all embryonic stages
  - Larger protein mobility decreases in older embryos
  - Movement becomes more restricted as development progresses
- Developmental regulation of plasmodesmatal permeability controls:
  - Which signaling molecules can move between cells
  - Thereby influencing pattern formation
- Changes in symplastic connectivity define developmental domains

== Embryo Lethal Mutants

#figure(
  image(images.at("22.11").path, width: 50%),
)

- *Embryo lethal mutants* (胚胎致死突变体) arrest at various developmental stages
- Representative examples reveal essential genes:
  - *HSN4*: Involved in histidine biosynthesis
  - *TTN10*: Participates in mitotic DNA replication initiation
  - *EMB3001*: Contributes to proteolysis pathways
- These mutants cannot progress to maturity, indicating genes are essential for embryogenesis
- Reveal fundamental cellular processes required for embryo development
- Screens identify hundreds of genes essential for normal embryogenesis

== Seedling Defective Mutants

#figure(
  image(images.at("22.12").path, width: 50%),
)

- *Seedling defective mutants* (幼苗缺陷突变体) reveal genes essential for specific developmental processes:
  - *GNOM* gene: Establishes apical-basal polarity
    - gnom mutants show disordered embryo organization
    - Affects vesicle trafficking and auxin transport
  - *MONOPTEROS* (MP) gene: Necessary for basal patterning and primary root formation
    - monopteros mutants have hypocotyl, shoot apical meristem, and cotyledons
    - But lack primary root
    - MP is an *auxin response factor* (ARF, 生长素响应因子)
- Different genes control development of distinct embryo regions
- Deletion mutants lack specific embryonic domains present in wild type

= Auxin Signaling During Embryogenesis

== PIN1-Dependent Auxin Transport

#figure(
  image(images.at("22.13").path, width: 50%),
)

- Auxin functions as a mobile morphogenic signal during embryogenesis
- *PIN1* protein is an auxin *efflux carrier* (外排载体) that directs auxin movement
- Auxin movement patterns:
  - Inferred from asymmetric PIN1 protein distribution in membranes
  - Monitored using *DR5* auxin-responsive reporter
  - Blue areas show cells with maximum auxin concentrations
  - Brown shading indicates developing vascular cylinder
- Auxin maxima resulting from local synthesis create gradients
- These gradients are reinforced and maintained by polar PIN1 orientation
- Directional auxin transport creates concentration gradients specifying cell fates

== Evidence for Auxin's Role

#figure(
  image(images.at("22.14").path, width: 50%),
)

- Comparison of wild-type and mutant embryos reveals auxin's importance:
  - Wild-type: Normal cotyledon separation and bilateral symmetry
  - *pin1* mutants: Failure in cotyledon separation
  - Chemical inhibition of auxin transport produces similar phenotypes
- Proper auxin transport and gradient formation essential for:
  - Correct embryonic pattern establishment
  - Cotyledon initiation and separation
  - Vascular tissue differentiation
- PIN1 localizes to basal ends of transporting cells (consistent with chemiosmotic model)
- Auxin responses differ depending on target cell type and concentration

= Radial Patterning During Embryogenesis

== Sequence of Radial Patterning Events

#figure(
  image(images.at("22.15").path, width: 50%),
)

- Radial patterning progressively subdivides embryo into concentric tissue layers
- Sequence of tissue layer formation:
  - *Protoderm* (原表皮): First layer to be delineated, becomes epidermis
  - *Ground tissue* (基本组织): Forms cortex and endodermis
  - *Vascular tissue* (维管组织): Last to differentiate, forms xylem and phloem
- Number of tissue layers increases through action of *initial cells* (原始细胞)
- Initial cells undergo regulated periclinal divisions to generate new layers
- Each tissue layer acquires distinct identity through specific gene expression

== Epidermal Identity Genes

#figure(
  image(images.at("22.16").path, width: 50%),
)

- *ATML1* and *PDF2* transcription factors required for normal epidermis establishment
- Double atml1/pdf2 mutants:
  - Superficial layers resemble mesophyll rather than epidermis
  - Lack distinct epidermal characteristics
  - Outer cells fail to acquire epidermal identity
  - Instead adopt ground tissue characteristics
- These genes are essential for specifying epidermal cell fate
- Expressed in outer layer cells from early embryonic stages
- Direct expression of genes conferring epidermal properties

== Cytokinin and Vascular Development

#figure(
  image(images.at("22.17").path, width: 50%),
)

- *WOODEN LEG* (*WOL*) gene encodes cytokinin receptor (also called *CYTOKININ RESPONSE 1*, CRE1)
- wol mutants show:
  - Absence of phloem elements
  - Decreased cell layer numbers
  - Vascular tissue contains xylem but lacks phloem
- WOL/CRE1 required for critical cell division producing xylem and phloem precursors
- Demonstrates *cytokinin* (细胞分裂素) plays essential role in:
  - Radial pattern establishment
  - Vascular tissue differentiation
  - Proper periclinal divisions in procambium

== TMO5 and LHW Control Vascular Proliferation

#figure(
  image(images.at("22.18").path, width: 50%),
)

- *TMO5* and *LHW* transcription factors control vascular cell file numbers
- tmo5/tmo5-like1 double mutants show:
  - Reduced vascular tissue in mature embryos
  - Fewer vascular cells in root meristems
  - Fewer phloem poles
- Overexpression experiments:
  - TMO5 alone: moderate increase in vascular cells
  - TMO5 + LHW together: substantial increase in vascular cell files
- These factors act together as *heterodimers* (异源二聚体) to regulate:
  - Vascular proliferation
  - Cell division in procambial cells
  - Proper vascular system size

== Mutant Radial Root Patterns

#figure(
  image(images.at("22.19").path, width: 50%),
)

- Comparison of mutants reveals spatially defined gene functions:
  - *wooden leg* (wol): Lacks phloem tissue
  - *scarecrow* (scr): Lacks cortex layer
  - *short root* (shr): Disrupted ground tissue organization
- Each mutant specifically affects particular tissue layers while leaving others intact
- Demonstrates distinct genetic programs control formation of each radial tissue layer:
  - Epidermis: ATML1, PDF2
  - Cortex: SCR, SHR
  - Vasculature: WOL, TMO5, LHW
- Radial patterning involves sequential specification of tissue identities

== SHORT ROOT and SCARECROW Functions

#figure(
  image(images.at("22.20").path, width: 50%),
)

- *SHR* and *SCR* genes control tissue patterning through transcriptional regulation and protein movement:
  - SHR promoter activity restricted to *stele* (中柱)
  - But SHR protein moves to adjacent *endodermis* (内皮层) nuclei
  - Demonstrates cell-to-cell protein movement from synthesis site
- SCR expression patterns:
  - Wild-type: SCR transcribed in *quiescent center* (静止中心), endodermis, and cortical-endodermal initials
  - shr mutants: SCR expression abolished
  - Shows SHR protein regulates SCR gene expression
- Mobile transcription factors coordinate radial patterning across tissue layers
- Non-cell-autonomous gene action is critical for pattern formation

== Model for Root Cell Identity Specification

#figure(
  image(images.at("22.21").path, width: 50%),
)

- Sequential gene expression cascade specifies root cell identities:
  - (A) Early auxin-dependent expression of *MONOPTEROS* (MP) and *NPH4* (NONPHOTOTROPIC HYPOCOTYL 4) in basal domain
  - (B) MP and NPH4 promote *PLETHORA* (*PLT*, 丰富) gene expression
  - (C) PLT induces *SCARECROW* (SCR) and *SHORT ROOT* (SHR) expression
- Combination of PLT, SCR, and SHR expression:
  - Directs centrally positioned cells to become quiescent center
  - Induces *WOX5* expression maintaining surrounding initial cells
- This regulatory cascade shows how:
  - Auxin initiates a transcriptional network
  - Network progressively specifies distinct cell types
  - Establishes root apical meristem organization
- Different transcription factor combinations create distinct cell fates

= Formation of Root and Shoot Apical Meristems

== Mutually Inhibitory Transcription Factor Interactions

#figure(
  image(images.at("22.22").path, width: 50%),
)

- Shoot and root apical meristems initiated through antagonistic transcription factor interactions
- In 16-cell embryo:
  - Upper tier gives rise to shoot domain
  - Lower tier gives rise to root domain
- Central regulatory mechanism:
  - *HD-Zip III* transcription factors in upper tier promote shoot initiation
  - *PLT* transcription factors in lower tier promote root initiation
  - These factors mutually inhibit each other's expression
- Additional regulatory mechanisms:
  - *BODENLOS* (*BDL*) and *TOPLESS* (*TPL*) control PLT expression
  - MicroRNA *miR165/166* from lower tier restricts HD-Zip III mRNA to upper tier
- Mutual antagonism establishes opposite meristem identities in distinct domains

== Ectopic Expression Experiments

- Overexpression experiments demonstrate transcription factor sufficiency:
  - PLT overexpression in shoot: Produces root meristems with *statoliths* (平衡石)
    - Statoliths are starch-filled plastids characteristic of root cells
    - Demonstrates PLT can reprogram shoot cells to root fate
  - HD-Zip III overexpression in lower tier: Creates second shoot domain
    - Shows HD-Zip III can reprogram root cells to shoot fate
- These experiments prove:
  - Transcription factors are sufficient to specify meristem identity
  - Proper spatial restriction is essential for normal development
  - Balance between antagonistic factors determines which meristem forms

== Shoot Apical Meristem Specification

- *SHOOT MERISTEMLESS* (*STM*) and *WUSCHEL* (*WUS*) genes essential for shoot meristem formation:
  - Both expressed in apical domain of young embryos
  - Neither alone can form new shoot apical meristems when ectopically expressed
  - Together they can initiate meristem formation
- Position of embryonic shoot apical meristem defined by:
  - Domain where STM and WUS expression overlaps
  - Integration with HD-Zip III activity
- Shoot meristem maintains *stem cells* (干细胞) for continuous growth
- *Central zone* (中央区) contains slowly dividing stem cells
- *Peripheral zone* (周边区) produces organ primordia

= Developmental Plasticity and Alternative Embryogenesis

#figure(
  image(images.at("22.23").path, width: 50%),
)

== Multiple Cell Types Can Initiate Embryogenesis

- Embryogenesis occurs not only from zygotes but from various cell types
- Natural asexual embryogenesis:
  - *Apomixis* (无融合生殖): Asexual embryogenesis from somatic cells within ovule
  - Somatic embryogenesis from leaf margin (e.g., in *Kalanchoe*, 落地生根)
- Artificially induced embryogenesis:
  - *Somatic embryogenesis* from callus tissue following hormone treatments
    - Used for plant propagation
    - Requires treatment with auxin and cytokinin
  - Microspore embryogenesis: Stress (e.g., heat) induces embryo formation from pollen precursors
  - Suspensor cell embryogenesis: If embryo proper is damaged, suspensor cells can form second embryo

== Developmental Potential of Plant Cells

- Given appropriate triggers, plant cells of many types can form embryos
- Attests to tremendous developmental potential and *totipotency* (全能性) of plant cells
- Alternative embryos often morphologically indistinguishable from zygotic embryos
- Suggests embryogenic program can be activated by:
  - Specific developmental signals
  - Environmental triggers
  - Hormonal treatments
- Practical applications:
  - Plant breeding and propagation
  - Genetic transformation
  - Crop improvement through tissue culture

= Summary and Integration

== Key Concepts of Embryogenesis

- Sporophyte generation begins with fertilization events initiating embryogenesis
- Regulated cell divisions produce polar axis and bilateral symmetry
- Both mobile signals (hormones) and positional signals function as morphogenic regulators
- Extended regulatory mechanisms function in further organ elaboration during postembryonic growth

== Establishment of Polarity

- Apical-basal polarity established early in embryogenesis
- First zygotic division is asymmetric, producing apical and basal cells with different fates
- Cytoskeletal reorganization precedes and guides asymmetric division
- Auxin gradients reinforce and maintain polarity

== Position-Dependent Cell Fate Determination

- Cell fate determined by position and signaling environment, not strict lineage
- Positional information more important than precise cell division patterns
- Pattern formation is robust to perturbations
- Intercellular communication through plasmodesmata enables coordination

== Radial Patterning

- Progressive subdivision creates concentric tissue layers
- Specific transcription factors specify each layer identity:
  - Epidermis: ATML1, PDF2
  - Ground tissue: SCR, SHR
  - Vascular tissue: WOL, TMO5, LHW
- Mobile transcription factors coordinate patterning across layers

== Apical Meristem Formation

- Mutually inhibitory transcription factors establish opposite meristem identities
- HD-Zip III promotes shoot; PLT promotes root
- Meristems maintain stem cells for indeterminate growth
- Postembryonic plants retain meristems for plastic, adaptive growth

== Developmental Flexibility

- Many cell types can undergo embryogenesis under appropriate conditions
- Demonstrates tremendous developmental potential of plant cells
- Practical applications in agriculture and biotechnology
- Evolutionary significance: embryogenesis older than seed development
